From b0a1891c6a011e9cd2eb352a829788f522b5eaaf Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Philippe Gerum <philippe.gerum@exail.com>
Date: Tue, 12 Mar 2024 14:12:49 +0100
Subject: [PATCH 137/174] genirq: irq_pipeline: skip IRQ forwarding when
 running oob

A subsequent oob event might arrive before its handler had a chance to
process a pending forwarded interrupt from the in-band stage.

Since we don't want to delay interrupts when oob handlers exist, we
cannot mask them and/or defer EOI until the in-band stage did process
them. To address the issue, let's ignore forwarding if the oob stage
is current in forward_irq_event().

As a result, the semantics of IRQ forwarding requires the oob-side of
the interrupt handler to decode and record all forwarded events as
many times as it might be called in a row, until the in-band side is
able to process all of them in one go eventually.

Signed-off-by: Philippe Gerum <philippe.gerum@exail.com>
---
 kernel/irq/chip.c | 10 ++++++----
 1 file changed, 6 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/kernel/irq/chip.c b/kernel/irq/chip.c
index 5066b2c938c6..2fe9aa5f8400 100644
--- a/kernel/irq/chip.c
+++ b/kernel/irq/chip.c
@@ -532,11 +532,13 @@ void irq_clear_forward(struct irq_desc *desc)
 
 static irqreturn_t forward_irq_event(struct irq_desc *desc)
 {
-	irqreturn_t ret;
+	irqreturn_t ret = IRQ_HANDLED;
 
-	raw_spin_unlock(&desc->lock);
-	ret = handle_irq_event_percpu(desc);
-	raw_spin_lock(&desc->lock);
+	if (likely(running_inband())) {
+		raw_spin_unlock(&desc->lock);
+		ret = handle_irq_event_percpu(desc);
+		raw_spin_lock(&desc->lock);
+	}
 
 	return ret;
 }
